IMHO:

Not so fast unless you want to rebuild your engine sooner than necessary!!
 The
engine gets maybe 30 seconds to a minute before I go above 1500 RPM.

When I worked on aircraft engines, we were always told not to exceed 1000
RPM until you had 125 degrees F. of cyl head temp plus oil temp had to start
increasing.
Seems like the risk of scouring dry cyl walls would be greater if you rev up
the engine. I think that extra idling uses extra gas and emits extra
polution but saves the engine.
